from the Ebola River in the northern Congo (former Zaire) ◆According to Peter Piot, a Belgian member of an international commission formed to investigate the first outbreak of the virus in 1976, the name was chosen by members of the commission (including the French physician Pierre Sureau and the Americans Karl Johnson and Joel Breman) from a map of Zaire at the Fonds Médical Tropical, a non-governmental organization in Kinshasa where the members were lodged. Though the Ebola River (a headwater stream of the Mongala River, a tributary of the Congo) turned out to be a considerable distance from the village of Yambuku where the fever was first observed, the name was nonetheless retained. The name “Yambuku virus” was avoided because of the stigma it would have attached to the village. (See Peter Piot, No Time to Lose: A Life in Pursuit of Deadly Viruses, W.W. borrowed from French crymothérapie, from crymo- crymo- + -thérapie therapy ◆Term introduced by the French physicians Maurice Letulle and Élisée Ribard in “Essai de crymothérapie locale dans la tuberculose pulmonaire,” Bulletins et mémoires de la Société Médicale des Hôpitaux de Paris, 3. série, tome 15 (1898), p. 261: “C’est dans ce but que nous avons eu recours aux basses températures appliquées localement sur la région gastrique. Nous avons donné à ce nouveau mode de traitement le nom de Crymothérapie, de [Greek letters] Krymos, grand froid, comme indiquant de façon plus précise que frigothérapie ou cryothérapie, la signification exacte de ce nouveau procédé.” (“With this aim we had resorted to low temperatures applied locally over the gastric area. We have given to this new method of treatment the name crymotherapy, from Krymos, great cold, as marking the exact significance of this new procedure in a more precise manner than frigotherapy or cryotherapy.”) The word frigothérapie was used earlier by the Swiss physicist Raoul Pictet (in La frigotheérapie : ses origines, son but, les résultats déja obtenus, Paris, 1898, and in several periodical publications dating back to 1895 or earlier). Though Letulle and Ribard allude to cryothérapie as if it already existed, it is unclear who first employed it. Curiously, later authors appear to have quickly adapted the authors’ crymothérapie into cryothérapie (German Kryotherapie, English cryotherapy); cf., for example, the following report in Merck’s Archives, vol. 3, no. 11 (November, 1901): “An original method of treating anorexia has been introduced by Letule [sic] and Ribaud; they call the method cryo-therapy (from kryos, frost) … .”

borrowed from New Latin, from Greek chlamyd-, chlamýs “cloak, mantle” + New Latin -ia -ia (after earlier New Latin Chlamydozoon chlamydozoon)  — more at chlamys  ◆Name first proposed as a taxon by Helen Jones, Geoffrey Rake and Barbara Stearns in “Studies on lymphogranuloma venereum III. The action of the sulfonamides on the agent of lymphogranuloma venereum,” Journal of Infectious Diseases, vol. 76, no. 1 (January-February, 1945), p. 55: “In fact, the only so-called viruses whose susceptibility to the sulfonamides has been confirmed are members of the lymphogranuloma-trachoma-psittacosis group of agents (namely, lymphogranuloma venereum, trachoma, inclusion blenorrhea [sic], and mouse pneumonitis). Evidence has accumulated serving to separate this group from the true viruses, and place it in a position between the bacteria and the viruses, analogous to the Rickettsiae, with the name Chlamydia.” In the seventh edition of Bergey’s Manual of Determinative Bacteriology (Baltimore, 1957), pp. 957-59, Geoffrey Rake treats the 1945 introduction as a nomen nudum and in effect reintroduces the taxon, with the species Chlamydia trachomatis and C. oculogenitalis. Rake indicates that Chlamydia is a replacement for the earlier genus name Chlamydozoon (used in the sixth edition of Bergey’s Manual), which had been disallowed taxonomically on the grounds that the type species, Chlamydozoon bombycis, was actually a virus (see note herein at chlamydozoon). Subsequently, the 1945 introduction of Chlamydia has been regarded as valid (see Leslie A. Page, “Revision of the family Chlamydiaceae Rake (Rickettsiales): Unification of the psittacosis-lymphogranuloma venereum-trachoma group of organisms in the genus Chlamydia Jones, Rake and Stearns 1945,” International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, vol. 16, no. 2 [April, 1966], pp. 223-52).First Known Use: 1966 (sense 1)

borrowed from Kimakonde (Bantu language of the Makonde), alleged to mean “that which bends up” ◆Both the disease and the Kimakonde word were first reported in Marion C. Robinson, “An Epidemic of Virus Disease in Southern Province, Tanganyika Territory, in 1953-53. I. Clinical Features,” Transactions of the Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene, vol. 49, no. 1 (January, 1955), pp. 28-32. According to Robinson, “The epidemic to be described occurred on the Makonde Plateau in the Southern Province of Tanganyika … Owing to the distinctive severity of the joint pains and the sudden onset a local name was rapidly applied; the disease became known as chikungunya, meaning—‘that which bends up’.” An immediately following article in the same issue of the journal by W.H.R. Lumsden (“An Epidemic of Virus Disease in Southern Province, Tanganyika Territory, in 1953-53. II. General Description and Epidemiology,” pp. 33-57) amplifies this somewhat: “The disease was at an early time given a Kimakonde name—chikungunya. According to an educated local chief this word is derived from a root verb—kungunyala—meaning to dry up or become contorted, and signifies the cause of a contortion or folding. It is thought to be a new word only as applied to the disease, not as to its other uses which refer to the drying of leaves and the reaction of the sensitive plant. (p. 39)”First Known Use: 1955

chemo- + Greek dekt-, stem of verbal adjective and agentive derivatives (such as dektós “to be received, acceptable,” apodéktēs “receiver”) of déchesthai, Ionic dékesthai “to accept, receive” + -oma  — more at pandect  ◆Word introduced by R.M. Mulligan, a University of Colorado Medical School pathologist, in “Chemodectoma in the Dog,” abstract of a presentation given at the 47th Annual Meeting of the American Association of Pathologists and Bacteriologists (April 13-15, 1950), published in American Journal of Pathology, vol. 26, no. 4 (July, 1950), pp. 680-81. According to the author, “Chemodectoma (chemeia = infusion; dechesthai = to receive; oma = tumor) is a neoplasm consisting of chemoreceptor (chemodector) cells, which are associated with the distribution of parasympathetic nerves and which originate either in the adventitia of blood vessels in structures intimately connected with afferent nerve fibers, or which occur along the branches or in the ganglia of the glossopharyngeal and vagus nerves.” Mulligan apparently intended chemodect- as a Hellenized form of “chemoreceptor,” though his etymologizing is somewhat faulty, in that Greek chēmeía, ultimately the source of chemo-, is not attested textually in the meaning “infusion,” and -ōma is a suffix—not a noun—that has come to have the meaning “tumor” only in modern coinages. According to an editorial in JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association (“Biography of a Word – Chemodectoma: 1950-?”, vol. 187, no. 13 [March 28, 1964]), the word was gaining increasing acceptance at that time; however, to judge by more recent data from the National Library of Medicine’s PubMed index, chemodectoma has now receded in favor of the older term paraganglioma.First Known Use: 1950

Greek kapnós “smoke, steam” (of which carbon dioxide is a component) + -o- + -graph; kapnós, if going back to *kwap-no-, perhaps an outcome of Indo-European *k(w)uh2ep- and hence akin to Latin vapor “exhalation, steam, warmth,” and, from different vowel grades of a base *k(w)h2up-, Lithuanian kvãpas “smell, scent,” kvėpti (with circumflex) “to breathe in,” kūpúoti “to breathe heavily,” Latvian kûpt “to give off smoke” ◆The hypothesis of a connection between kapnós, Latin vapor (see 1vapor) and the set of Baltic words given above has been revived by Peter Schrijver in The Reflexes of the Proto-Indo-European Laryngeals in Latin (Rodopi, 1991), pp. 260-63, from whom the starred forms have been adapted. Comparanda have been adduced from other languages, such as Gothic afhvapjan “to choke, extinguish,” afhvapnan “to choke” (and more remotely Icelandic hvap “flesh swollen by edema,” Middle High German verwepfen “to become fusty—of wine”), though the p in these words would reflect Indo-European b rather than p; also Russian kopot’ “soot,” koptit’ “to cure with smoke,” and Slavic cognates, though these words lack the internal *-u-. (Note the comment of Hjalmar Frisk, Griechisches etymologisches Wörterbuch, in regard to this etymon, that one has to deal with “many not unexpected derailments”—“Man hat somit in den verschiedenen Sprachen mit zahlreichen, nicht unerwarteten Entgleisungen zu rechnen.”) Regarding Greek kapnós, Robert Beekes in Etymological Dictionary of Greek (Brill, 2010) believes any Indo-European etymology is doubtful, and that the etymon may reflect either pre-Greek or European substratum.First Known Use: 1964

borrowed from Spanish or Italian bomba or French bombe, all probably in part from an onomatopoeic base bomb- (as in Greek bómbos “booming, humming,” Old Norse bumba “drum,” Lithuanian bambėti “to mutter, mumble,” Albanian bumbullin “it is thundering”), in part back-formation from Medieval Latin bombardus or Middle French bombarde 1bombard ◆The origin and transmission of bomba, bombe, etc., in the sense “explosive device, projectile, etc.,” among European languages is not certain. Bomba is attested earliest in Spanish, appearing several times in the second half of the 16th century (canto 18 of La Araucana of Alonso de Ercilla y Zúñiga, the Descripción general de {Aactue}frica of Luis del Mármol, the Historia de las cosas … del Gran Reyno de la China of Juan González de Mendoza). Mendoza’s book (1585) is the source of an early and aberrant instance of bomb in English: his bombas de fuego is rendered as “bomes of fire” in Robert Parke’s translation (The Historie of the Great and Mightie Kingdome of China, London, 1588, p. 65). Bomba is recorded as Italian in Antoine Oudin’s Italian-French dictionary (Recherches italiennes et françoises, Paris, 1640), where it is glossed “bombe, ou balon de feu” (“bomb, or ball of fire”), though it is not recorded in an Italian text until 1686 (Paolo Segneri, Il cristiano instruito, Florence, p. 327); Oudin’s gloss also apparently constitutes the first record in French. Significantly earlier than any of these is Latin bombus, which occurs twice in the Commentarii, an account of the exploits of the condottiero Jacopo Piccinino in 1452-53 by the Neapolitan humanist Giannantonio de’ Pandone, “il Porcellio” (ca. 1405-85); Pandone’s bombus appears to be some sort of exploding projectile (“Hic Tibertus Dux bombi fulmine in ulna sauciatur” - “Here Duke Tibertus [the condottiero Tiberto Brandolini] was wounded in the forearm by the flash of a bombus”); the 18th-century lexicographer Du Cange, in Glossarium mediae et infimae Latinitatis, glosses bombus in this passage, alluding to French bombe, as pila incendiaria, “fireball.” Spanish bomba in the sense “pump,” attested from the early 16th century, is almost certainly an independent formation; cf. 1pump.First Known Use: 1662 (sense 1a)

by insertion of bio- into atrophy ◆The word was introduced by the British neurologist William R. Gowers (1845–1915) in “A Lecture on Abiotrophy,” published in The Lancet (vol. 159, no. 4102, April 12, 1902, pp. 1003-08). Gowers gives an explicit account of his thought process in coining the word: “I do not like new words—indeed, I dislike them—but if we have a conception for which no name exists, which we need frequently to speak of, it is not wise, I think, to shrink from an attempt to give it a name. Here the simplest mode of obtaining what we need is to insert the root of bíos [Greek letters] after the negative particle in ‘atrophy’ which gives us ‘abiotrophy’. But it is generally better, if you can, to appropriate what you need than to make it afresh, and we find the word biotrophos [Greek letters] used in the sense of ‘vital nutrition’. If we prefix the negative particle we have the same word, ‘abiotrophy’. [In footnote] 2 Not indeed in classical Greek; it is quoted by Stephanus from Gorgias [i.e., Georgias] Pisides, a Byzantine writer of the seventh century (620  a.d.).” The “Stephanus” that Gowers cites is the 16th-century French lexicographer Henricus Stephanus/Henri Estienne, though the word biotróphos appears only in the revised and supplemented edition of Stephanus’ Thesauròs tês Hellēnikês Glṓssēs/Thesaurus Graecae Linguae, edited by Charles Benoît Hase and Wilhelm and Ludwig Dindorf (Paris, 1832-65); vol. 2, p. 259 of this work contains the entry “biotróphos … Vitam nutriens [“nourishing life”]. Georg. Pisid. 406. B ast.” (“Bast[ius]” marking a contribution by the German Hellenist Friedrich Jacob Bast). The Greek dictionary of Liddell and Scott records an earlier instance of biotróphos, in an appendix to the Greek Anthology.First Known Use: 1902
